<!DOCTYPE theorem	SYSTEM "../Symbols.dtd">
<theorem xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
	xmlns="http://webmath.math.ualberta.ca/v1/Theorem"    xsi:schemaLocation="http://webmath.math.ualberta.ca/v1/Theorem    http://webmath.math.ualberta.ca/Schemas/v1/Theorem.xsd"
	type="Proposition" id="thm_DistanceBetweenPoints">
	<caption>Distance between Points</caption>
	<associate Description="Example">
		<showme.pack.ref showmePackID="Exa_DistancePoints"/>
		<info><para>Examples on computing the distance between points.</para></info>
	</associate>
	<associate Description="Explanation">
		<subpage.ref subpageID="Expl_DistancePoints"/>
		<info>
			<caption>Explanation</caption>
			<para>This formula is a consequence of the Theorem of Pythagoras. &ndash; See details of this</para>
		</info>
	</associate>
	<statement>
		<para>The distance between two points in <latex>P(x_1,\dots ,x_n)</latex> and <latex>Q(y_1,\dots
			,y_n)</latex> in <latex>\RNr[n]</latex> is given by</para>
		<math.display>
			<latex>\Dstnc{P}{Q}\ =\ \sqrt{(y_1-x_1)^2+\cdots + (y_n-x_n)^2}\ \ .</latex>
		</math.display>
	</statement>
	
<!--	<proof.ext>
		<caption>Using ordinary induction</caption>
		<para>We use induction on the dimension <latex>n</latex> of <latex>\RNr[n]</latex></para>
		<step>
			<caption>Anchoring the induction</caption>
			<pilot>
				<step>
					<para>To start the induction, we anchor it by verifying the claim for <latex>P</latex> and
						<latex>Q</latex> in <latex>RNr[1]</latex>
