				and <latex>t</latex> on a line. If <latex>t\geq s</latex>, we are in the situation depicted
				below.</para>
			
			<para align="justify"><img src="ims/DistancePoints_Prop_R.gif"/></para>
			
			<para>Note that <latex>|t-s|=|s-t|</latex>. So, actually, we don't need to worry which of the two numbers is bigger. The claim follows for <latex>n=1</latex> because</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>\text{dist}(P,Q)\ =\ |t-s|\ =\ \sqrt{(t-s)^2}.</latex>
			</math.display>
		</step>
		<step>
			<caption>Carrying out the induction step</caption>
			<pilot>
				<step>
					<para>Next we need to carry out the induction step.</para>
				</step>
			</pilot>
			<para>Assume now that the distance formula is valid in <latex>\RNr[n-1]</latex>, for <latex>n-1\geq 1</latex>. We need to infer that the distance formula is valid in <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>. With the following setup we can use the Theorem of Pythagoras to accomplish this task. Let us write</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>
					<![CDATA[
					\begin{array}{rclclrcl}
					P & = & (x_1,\dots ,x_{n-1},x_n) & = & (R,x_n) & \qquad R & = & (x_1,\dots ,x_{n-1}) \\
					Q & = & (y_1,\dots ,y_{n-1},y_n) & = & (S,y_n) & \qquad S & = & (y_1,\dots ,y_{n-1})
					\end{array}
					]]>
				</latex>
			</math.display>
			<para>By induction hypothesis,</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>\text{dist}(R,S)\ =\ \sqrt{(y_1-x_1)^2+\cdots +(y_{n-1}-x_{n-1})^2}</latex>
			</math.display>
			<para>The following schematic picture tells us how this setup relates the problem of finding <latex>\text{dist}(P,Q)</latex> to the Theorem of Pythagoras</para>
			
			<para align="center">
				<img src="DistancePoints_Prop_Rn.gif"/>
			</para>
			
			<math.display>
				<latex>
					<![CDATA[
					\aligned
					\text{dist}^2(P,Q)\ &=\ \text{dist}^2(R,S)\ +\ \text{dist}^2(x_n,y_n) \\
					&=\ (y_1-x_1)^2\ +\ \cdots\ +\ (y_{n-1}-x_{n-1})^2\ +\ (y_n-x_n)^2
					\endaligned
					]]>
				</latex>
			</math.display>
			<para>Consequently,</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>\text{dist}(P,Q)\ =\ \sqrt{(y_1-x_1)^2\ +\ \cdots\ +\ (y_{n-1}-x_{n-1})^2\ +\ (y_n-x_n)^2}</latex>
			</math.display>
			<para>as claimed. In this computation we used that</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>\sqrt{\text{dist}^2(P,Q)}\ =\ |\text{dist}(P,Q)|\ =\ \text{dist}(P,Q).</latex>
			</math.display>
		</step>
